originalText:
A draft law banning the use and import of landmines has been prepared
by the Cambodian Mines Action Center (CMAC), a local newspaper reported
today.

"Our draft of the law contains serious penalties against anyone found
to be importing or laying landmines," Som Socheath, a CMAC official,
was quoted as saying.

An estimated eight to 10 million landmines are still buried in Cambodia
and some 300 people a month are killed or injured by mine explosions.

The draft law, which has been submitted to the Council of Ministers,
the cabinet, is expected to reach the National Assembly, or parliament,
later this year.

"Landmines in Cambodia will disappear when there is no more war," said
Chum Sambath, spokesman for the Defense Ministry.

Over the past two years, 27,000 hectares of land has been de-mined,
resulting in the destruction of 55,700 anti-personnel mines and 375
anti-tank mines.
